    "36326332": {
      "title": "Does intact pair status matter in the study of African American twins? the Carolina African American twin study of aging",
      "abstract": "In twin research, typically both members of a pair must participate. Survivorship of members of intact pairs compared to surviving members of nonintact twin pairs may reflect differences in psychosocial and health factors, and represent a potential selection bias relative to the general population. The purpose of the present study is to examine health, cognition, and well-being among members of African American intact twin pairs compared to individuals from nonintact twin pairs. Data from the Carolina African American Twin Study of Aging (CAATSA) were used for analyses. Subjects ranged in age from 25 to 89 years of age (mean=59.78 years, SD=12.84 years). CAATSA implements a 3-h protocol to collect data on demographics, health, cognition, and well-being. Data from one randomly selected member of each twin pair (N=78) was compared to data from surviving members of nonintact twin pairs (N=52). The results indicated significant differences on 11 of the 39 measures (i.e., age, education, forced expiratory volu..."
    }
